<font color="#FF0000">SOME THOUGHTS FOR ROBERT</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 21 20:52:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
You will be rewarded greatly if you go ahead.  It has been said, &quot;Fear not, for I am with you.&quot;  But my experience is that fear is very normal and healthy.  Remember, your daughter also has fears, of rejection, of lack of understanding, of someone from a different culture.  By understanding that you both have much the same fears, you can forge a common bond upon which your relationship can grow.  Go forward, fearfully but steadily, knowing that like the Veterans here, we all experience fear.  It is in overcoming that fear that we find commonality, friendships and companionship.  Learn to be her friend.  It will be a very rich and enlightening experience.<br><br>
Concerning your memories, they may not be completely correct.  Our minds tend to trick us sometimes.  Compare your memories as you receive them with some others if you can.  <br><br>
Also know that we all are unfinished works in progress. We all make mistakes.  You and I are not the same person that we were yesterday, or a year ago, or ten years ago.  Accept what you have done; it cannot be changed.  But don't live your life &quot;like a driver looking in the rear-view mirror&quot; while trying to drive the streets.  Use your experience to cope with the present, to do things as you now feel you should.  <br><br>
One final thought:  make a copy of this thread, and share it with your daughter.  It will become a point where you can begin talking.  Many of us have shared things here that we cannot share face-to-face.  
